184.body: Git Source Inherits: Ownable, Multicall, ReentrancyGuardTransient, IAdmiralsQuarters This contract uses an OpenZeppelin nonReentrant modifier with transient storage for gas efficiency. When it was developed the OpenZeppelin version was 5.0.2 ( hence the use of locally stored ReentrancyGuardTransient ) A contract for managing deposits and withdrawals to/from FleetCommander contracts, with integrated swapping functionality using 1inch Router. *How to use this contract: Deposit tokens: Use depositTokens to deposit ERC20 tokens into the contract. Withdraw tokens: Use withdrawTokens to withdraw deposited tokens. Enter a fleet: Use enterFleet to deposit tokens into a FleetCommander contract. Exit a fleet: Use exitFleet to withdraw tokens from a FleetCommander contract. Swap tokens: Use swap to exchange one token for another using the 1inch Router. Rescue tokens: Contract owner can use rescueTokens to withdraw any tokens stuck in the contract.* *Multicall functionality: This contract inherits from OpenZeppelin's Multicall, allowing multiple function calls to be batched into a single transaction. To use Multicall: Encode each function call you want to make as calldata. Pack these encoded function calls into an array of bytes. Call the multicall function with this array as the argument. Example Multicall usage: bytes[] memory calls = new bytes ; calls[0] = abi.encodeWithSelector(this.depositTokens.selector, tokenAddress, amount); calls[1] = abi.encodeWithSelector(this.enterFleet.selector, fleetCommanderAddress, tokenAddress, amount); (bool[] memory successes, bytes[] memory results) = this.multicall(calls);* *Security considerations: All external functions are protected against reentrancy attacks. The contract uses OpenZeppelin's SafeERC20 for safe token transfers. Only the contract owner can rescue tokens. Ensure that the 1inch Router address provided in the constructor is correct and trusted. Since there is no data exchange between calls - make sure all the tokens are returned to the user*
